# {{ _wt_slug }}

{{ wt.description | default('A shared work directory.') }}

This is the shared **work directory** for the project. The bare git repository
lives at `{{ _wt_repo }}`; this directory's `.git` file points at it, so you can
run git here to **look things up** — but you cannot edit anything from here (the
pad reports as a bare repo, so there is no working tree).

## Looking things up

Run git directly in this directory against the live repo:

```bash
git log --oneline -20 main              # recent history
git branch                              # what work is in flight
git show main:path/to/file              # read a file at a ref
git log --oneline <category>/<branch>   # someone's in-progress branch
```

## Doing work → use a worktree

Don't edit files here. Each piece of work gets its own worktree at
`{{ _wt_workdir }}/<category>/<branch>` on a branch of the same name,
`<category>/<branch>` — exactly what a plain `git worktree add` there would use.

Claude users: ask Claude to call the **`EnterWorktree`** tool (or start with
`claude --worktree <category>/<branch>` from the CLI). Both routes go through
`.claude/hooks/worktree-create`, which creates the worktree and its branch.

The name is **`<category>/<branch>`**:

- `<category>` is just a folder under this work directory grouping related work.
  There's no allowlist — a new category folder is created on demand. This
  project starts with: {% for c in _wt_categories %}`{{ c }}`{{ ", " if not loop.last else "" }}{% endfor %}.
- `<branch>` is a URL slug: lowercase `a-z`/`0-9`, start with a letter, contain
  at least one `-`, at most 40 characters — e.g. `add-dns-role`, `fix-login`.

So: `feature/add-dns-role`, `fix/login-redirect`, `experiment/new-router`.

### Choosing a base

A new worktree's branch is always cut from **`main`**, wherever you create it
from. That keeps unrelated work out of your branch and your eventual MR
reviewable.

Before starting, decide whether `main` is the right base for *this* work:

- **Does other, unmerged work belong in it?** If your change builds on an open
  MR or another feature branch, you want that work present. Either base the new
  branch on it directly (pass that branch instead of `main` to
  `git worktree add … -b …`), or start from `main` and **merge the other branch
  in** once you're in the worktree (`git merge <branch>`).
- **Is it independent?** Then plain `main` is right — leave it.

`EnterWorktree` always gives you a `main`-based worktree, so to build on another
branch pull it in once you're inside:

```bash
git merge <category>/<other-branch>
```

Prefer the smallest base that gets the job done: merging a branch in is explicit
and visible in the log, whereas basing on it silently pulls its (possibly
in-review) history into yours.

## Who merges what

Open an MR against `main`; the maintainer reviews and merges. Don't push to
`main` from a worktree branch — the bare repo's hooks will reject it.

See [Shared Worktrees 🌳](https://cute-devops.patterns.how/patterns/approaches/shared-worktrees) for the full pattern.

